# planning-env-var-to-typed-cli-option-migration -- History

## v1.1.0 (2026-06-24)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus Issue #1526, R1 planning pass (second pass) -- assumptions verified against actual code
**Verification:** unverified (still a PLAN; never executed, no CI)

### What changed
- Converted six R0 "assumptions to flag" into VERIFIED planning patterns after the
  plan author got a NOGO on R0's implementation plan and then READ the actual code:
  - **Per-knob granularity is the faithful mapping.** R0 collapsed 9 distinct
    agent-timeout env vars onto one `agent_timeout` per command and got a NOGO for
    dropping per-knob operator tunability. Faithful mapping = one flag + one typed
    field PER knob; a shared sub-agent knob (`advise`) invoked from 3 commands gets
    its OWN `advise_timeout` field on EACH command's options class.
  - **The "every leaf holds self.options" assumption was VERIFIED FALSE for free
    functions.** Four call sites are module-level free functions
    (`learn.run_learn`, `follow_up.run_follow_up_issues`,
    `comment_difficulty.classify_comments`, `pr_manager._invoke_git_message_agent`
    via the `commit_changes`/`create_pr` chain). The fix mirrors an EXISTING threaded
    param: these free functions already accept `model=`/`agent=` threaded down from an
    option-holding method; the timeout threads the identical way.
  - **A shared free-function entry invoked from multiple option-holders takes the
    union of params.** `run_address_fix_session` (called from 3 option-holders) gains
    `address_review_timeout` + `advise_timeout` + `git_message_timeout` and forwards
    each; each caller passes its own `self.options.*`.
  - **Blast radius verified empirically:** R0 claimed 36 importers; ground truth was
    18 (the 36 counted git-worktree duplicates). Over-counting wrongly motivates
    delete-and-rewrite over keeping a constants module.
  - **Keep the env-reading module as a CONSTANTS module** (already in R0, now
    reinforced as the correct call vs deleting it).
  - **Pick BOTH an easy (method, already holds options) and a hard (free-function)
    representative threading test;** the free-function path is where migration breaks.
  - **Test blast radius includes mocks to NON-default sentinels** (e.g. a test
    mocking `git_message_agent_timeout()` to 120); grep literal sentinel values too.
- Added tags: per-knob-granularity, free-function-threading, blast-radius-verification,
  constants-module.
- Added a `history:` frontmatter field.
- Bumped version 1.0.0 -> 1.1.0. Verification remains `unverified` (still a plan).
- Kept three genuinely-uncertain items as risk rows: `post_merge_processor`'s
  `learn_claude_timeout()` provider type (residual hand-wave), the surviving library
  -layer `HEPH_GH_CLI_TIMEOUT`, and drifting line numbers.

### Why
R0 (PR #2815) captured planning ASSUMPTIONS as RISKS. In R1 the author got a NOGO on
R0's implementation plan, then VERIFIED those assumptions by reading the real code in
`hephaestus/automation/`. The durable learning is now the CONFIRMED resolution of
those risks, so the existing skill was amended (not duplicated) to convert each
flagged assumption into a verified pattern while keeping the still-uncertain residuals
as risk rows.

### Previous version (v1.0.0) snapshot

```markdown
---
name: planning-env-var-to-typed-cli-option-migration
description: "Plan a migration that REMOVES operator-facing env-var knobs (e.g. HEPH_*_TIMEOUT) and replaces them with explicit CLI flags threaded through typed options objects, across a large fan-out of call sites. Method: map each env-reading helper 1:1 to the typed options object that ALREADY reaches its call site via self.options; keep the helper module as the single source of DEFAULT CONSTANTS (don't delete it); use a None-sentinel CLI flag + pydantic field default (POLA); centralize new flags in a shared add_*_arg(parser); make the env-removal a TESTED invariant (helper IGNORES env + inspect.getsource has no os.environ). Use when: (1) planning an env-var -> typed CLI option migration, (2) a config knob is read by a helper called from many sites, (3) some leaf callers are FREE FUNCTIONS that do NOT hold the options object and need a threaded timeout parameter, (4) collapsing multiple per-phase env knobs onto one options field risks removing operator tunability, (5) a different default (e.g. git_message_timeout=300s vs agent_timeout=7200s) must stay a SEPARATE field."
